Reasoning: The claim is strongly supported by evidence from a randomized controlled trial (Paper ID: 10582939). This study directly compared autologous mesenchymal stem cell (MSC) transplantation with anti-interleukin-2 receptor antibody induction therapy in living-related kidney transplant recipients. The results showed significantly lower rates of biopsy-confirmed acute rejection in the autologous MSC groups. Specifically, after 6 months, the acute rejection rates were 7.5% (4 of 53 patients) in the autologous MSC plus standard-dose CNI group (prop_1051) and 7.7% (4 of 52 patients) in the low-dose MSC group (prop_1052), compared to 21.6% (11 of 51 controls) in the anti-IL-2 receptor antibody control group (prop_1053). Furthermore, none of the MSC-treated patients experienced glucocorticoid-resistant rejection, while 7.8% (4 patients) in the control group did (prop_1054, prop_1055). The abstract of the paper explicitly concludes that autologous MSCs resulted in a lower incidence of acute rejection compared to anti-IL-2 receptor antibody induction therapy.
